SIMPLE: ornate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ornate
<hw>Or*nate"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>ornatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>ornare</ets> to adorn.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Elaborately adorned or decorated; beautifully
sumptuous.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧So bedecked, <xex>ornate</xex>, and gay.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Finely finished, as a style of
composition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A graceful and <qex>ornate</qex> rhetoric.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ornate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ornate
<hw>Or*nate"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To adorn; to honor.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They may <qex>ornate</qex> and sanctify the name of God.</q>
<rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ornately</ent>⟦br⟧
